Sharon Brackett is a serial entrepreneur who has help found and lead technology companies for the past decade. In 2011 she founded Tiresias Technologies, Inc. ( www.TiresiasTech.com ) as a new venture to address the unique technical needs of government and commercial interests in the Baltimore/Washington corridor. In 2010 she was selected by Washington SmartCEO Magazine as one of Washington's Smart100 CEOs for 2010 and then did it again in 2011.

Sharon is a seasoned engineering manager and business leader with over 25 years of experience in the computer and real-time systems development arena. Trained as a Computer Engineer, her background runs the range from hardware design and development to real-time operating systems to Internet and web applications development. In her career she has developed systems as complex as ground based telemetry systems, as large as multi-chassis networked real-time distributed control systems and as small as single chip embedded microcontroller devices.

Prior to founding Tiresias Technologies Sharon was President/CEO of the PTR Group. In her ten years there she grew the company from a startup to a staff of 35, and four consecutive appearances on the Inc. 5000 list of fastest growing companies from 2007-2010. Building a base of government and commercial customers that sustained that rapid growth.

Before her tenure at The PTR Group Sharon was a co-founder of Lightningcast, Inc. where she served as the VP of Business Development and was responsible for development of a business plan and model that resulted in $4.7MM in first round venture funding. Prior to that position, she served as Vice President of Customer and Engineering Services for Integrated Chipware, Inc. In the mid 1990's she founded, and managed, the Computer Products Division of SPARTA, Inc where she took division sales from $50K to $3.5M in less than 5 years. Prior to SPARTA she has held many positions as engineering manager, group head, and industry standards representative, in both the scientific instrumentation and medical imaging fields

She is a board member of MoringaCommunity.org, a charity that is building a trade school and food preservation education program in Ghana, West Africa. In her spare time she works with youth groups with technical interests such as rocketry and robotics and is active in civil rights and social justice concerns in the state of Maryland.

Not a whole lot to say about myself. I'm unemployed due to a medical disability (which the state won't recognize, /sigh), but have had the gift of great parents to provide a home for myself and my daughter. I attended college for graphic and web design, but since leaving, have taken it upon myself to learn electrical and mechanical engineering, embedded system design, robotics, and more. I have a thirst for knowledge, and find "down time" stressful. If I'm on the couch watching TV, I have my phone in my hand reading articles on the newest scientific research, or learning about a new electronics component, or one of many other things. I view television as a great source of background noise to quiet the "silence" that exists without and that fuels my already severe anxiety disorder. I have three 3d printers, two cartesian and one delta, as well as a filament extruder based on other designs, but designed from the ground up with parts I had available to me with those other designs as more inspiration than reference. I did purchase the official fil-a-winder accessory, however, as I was already well beyond frustrated at that point. I continue to try to learn more every day, until I consider myself skilled enough to be employable. I have wonderful parents that have provided a home for myself and my daughter in their in-law suite in the basement while I search for a way to make a living for the two of us. I hope that my research and the designs it leads to that I have and will continue to post here will aid me in finding an employer who may just see the value in taking on an apprentice that has all the passion, determination, and motivation in the world, has a strong work ethic regardless of the daily, constant pain fighting against him, and yet only severely lacks in the resources to accomplish his goals. I am constantly having new ideas for products or technologies, ideas that could change the way, in part, that we live our daily lives, but I have no way of coming close to realizing any of those ideas. But here's crossing my fingers, putting my best work out there, and doing what I can to make something of myself. As much as I hope one day someone will come along to fund my work, but I'm not stupid, and hard work is the only way it'll ever happen.

Statement from current occasion:
Inquiries from all over the world reach me, whether I sell 3D prints. Especially my slotcar-bodysuits. Of course I will not do that because I do not know the legal situation about protected vehicle designs.
There are rumors circulating on the Internet that nothing stands in the way of a sale of the vehicles, if one removes only the manufacturer and model designations as well as possibly existing emblems and gives the model a fancy name.
Also the sale or the free offer of the print file should supposedly be no problem, provided that I am the sole creator of the CAD file.
But it's not just about possibly necessary licenses of the manufacturer.
If I wanted to sell something officially, for example, through my homepage, then I have to register a trade under German law, because I may make a profit with the sale, for which I would have to pay taxes.

bio:
Hey, I'm Jake, and 3D printing is my favorite hobby. I really like solving problems, so I get a lot of satisfaction from 3D printing because while it comes with challenges of its own, it also enables a lot of solutions to everyday problems. :D

After spending a lot of my free time over the past 3 years slicing models in Cura, making models in SketchUp, and printing plastic things on a Printrbot Simple Metal, I think I've gotten an intuitive feel for the 3D printing process. Specifically, I really know what my printer will actually output given the settings of the slicer. It's a bit of a steep learning curve just getting good prints of proven models let alone going from a blank modeling window to a solid object in real life, but it's well worth it to be able to make an idea in your head into a tangible, usable object in the same day.

La Fablessy S.r.l. nasce come start up nel dicembre del 2014 come sintesi di un’idea nata molti mesi prima, con l'obbiettivo di fornire servizi legati al mondo della modellazione, prototipazione e stampa 3D ad aziende e privati, che avessero bisogno di un vero slancio innovativo per realizzare le loro idee.
Dopo aver fatto esperienza nell'ambito della stampa 3D con la costruzione di alcuni prototipi, di stampanti 3D e lavori prettamente per sviluppo e ricerca interni il team decide, data la maturità acquisita, di lanciarsi definitivamente sul mercato, aprendo una vera e propria sede fisica (gennaio 2016) e riuscendo in poco tempo a diventare uno dei punti di riferimento per il proprio territorio e, poi, a livello nazionale, affermandosi come uno dei migliori centri di modellazione e stampa 3D.
Attualmente Fablessy vanta varie partnership con diverse aziende del settore della stampa 3D come Ira3D, Eumakers, 3dmYd e Authentise e collaborazioni per la realizzazione di prototipi con molte aziende affermate sul territorio italiano come Pizzarotti, Teo Sport, Adamatica Group e tanti altri.

I'm proactively raising my kids to be makers. At 3.5 (son) and 0.7 (daughter) they've got a long ways to go, but between low power electronics (sensors and MCUs), robotics, and 3D printing I'm sure I'll hit something they gain traction on. If nothing else I hope to instill in them the core fundamental truth: if someone else made one (a company?) then we can make one too (and ours could be better).

Inventor, Maker, disruptive influence, mad scientist, Evil Genius.

I learned at an early age that it is possible to be too smart for one's own good. Some adults can feel quite threatened by encountering such a child... Sometimes these adults are in charge of your future, such as teachers, or psychologists... Following a failed attempt by several such adults to return me to the herd or cull me entirely, I fled underground, suffering a lasting and crippling social disability in the process. In the decades that followed, I have stayed hidden, in the dark corners of the internet which has raised me and taught me... Scheming, plotting, biding my time, until my day of reckoning is at hand!

The world has been warned.
